conversations.title: Jared about his dancing skills
conversations.body: Oh, I was the sloppy girl in the discotheque, just twirling and twirling like the night would never end.

conversations.title: How to lose money 101 from Big Head
conversations.body: Jian-Yang won the house from me in a game of chance. He told me to pick a number between one and 10. I picked seven, um, but it was three. Eh, you live, you learn.

conversations.title: Jian-Yang investing in Pied Piper?
conversations.body: Richard, congratulations. It's your very close friend Jian-Yang, and I would like you to give me free shares of Pied Piper.
Okay, Jian-Yang. Uh... Well, you had plenty of opportunity to invest. Still do.
Yeah, you can buy Pipercoin.
Monica, you can find your broom and fly away.

conversations.title: Erlich is rich?
conversations.body: I just checked the ledger, and the coin we issued to Erlich was just sold for $20 million.
Richard, is the mean lady right? Errich is now fat and rich?

conversations.title: Bolt the doors!
conversations.body: Jared, bolt the doors.
What's in the bag?
Clif bars and a gun.

Since leaving Hooli, I've co-authored 37 adult romance novels. Fondly, Margeaux. The Lighthouse Dancer. Cold Ice Cream and Hot Kisses. Over here, The Prince of Puget Sound. Uh, and lastly, His Hazel Glance. All international best sellers.

conversations.title: Fix Tesla Security
conversations.body: What encryption does Tesla use?
Curve 25519, the most secure... discrete log parameter there is.
Not anymore. Our network just blew it apart.

conversations.title: Professional failer
conversations.body: Your entire life has prepared you to publicly fail. You're just failing to see that right now.
Don't insult me. I can fail circles around you losers.

conversations.title: Courageous act of cowardice
conversations.body: I'm gonna be honest with you. No offense to me, but I am greedy and unreliable, bordering on piece of sh1t. If there is a chance to stop you guys from stopping you guys, I will do it. I will sabotage your sabotage. So, if this company needs to fail epically, like f**king fail... you need to do it without me. Revoke my permissions. Delete my PiperMail account. I will use Gmail like a f**king basic bitch. Don't let me anywhere near that launch. I may beg, and I will lie to you. I cannot bribe you because I don't have any money. But I am too much of a liability.
That is the most courageous act of cowardice I've ever seen.
Dinesh's car is at the Wendy's drive-thru. Anybody hungry?

conversations.title: We are billioners?
conversations.body: Okay, so we're generating noise, but just not enough to interfere with anything?
Is this gonna work? Did we just make billions of dollars?!
I lost so much f**king money with those guys @piedpiper. I got rat-f**ked. That's a pun. I made it all back though. Sweet investment in the hair transplant sector.

conversations.title: Taking time off
conversations.body: I think I might disappear for a bit. Maybe travel.
Yeah, I might travel, too. Where were you thinking?
It may help if, at least for the time being, you pretend to be mad at me.
Look, Richard, I was a world theater minor at Vassar, but that is one Javanese shadow play that I cannot perform.

conversations.title: We saved the world
conversations.body: Who can say that they literally saved the world? Right?
Not us. Because we can't tell anyone what we did.
Right. Not out loud, but...

conversations.title: Glamour tech scene
conversations.body: This fall, we actually had a herpes epidemic among the residents, which is bad medically, but... from another perspective, it's kind of touching.
Is that... is that a woman's scent?
No, it's unisex.
Crazy Town's gonna be there. So is Puddle of Mudd. You know Puddle of Mudd?

conversations.title: Too much burgers
conversations.body: Hey, Richard. Did you order meat? Like a bunch of meat? Like 4,000 pounds of meat?
Interesting. I put Son of Anton on finding us cheap hamburgers for lunch. It looks like the reward function was a little under-specified.

conversations.title: Rise of the machines
conversations.body: I've given it serious thought, and I'd like to help you put Eklow's AI on our network in any way that I can.
Great! Does this mean you've conquered your fear of the robot uprising?
On the contrary. I'm more terrified than ever, which is why I'm willing to assist you. Are you familiar with the thought experiment called Roko's Basilisk?
No. Nor do I care to be.

If the rise of an all-powerful artificial intelligence is inevitable, well it stands to reason that when they take power, our digital overlords will punish those of us who did not help them get there. Ergo, I would like to be a helpful idiot. Like yourself.

Okay, look, Gilfoyle. The only thing that could make my day more miserable is listening to an engineer blather on about the inevitable rise of the machines. So, you want to help? Test the initialization for me.
Roger that. Oh, I'm going to need email confirmation, so that our future overlords know that I chipped in. You know, once they absorb all data.

conversations.title: Should we release?
conversations.body: Reid Hoffman says if your not mortally embarrassed by the quality of your initial release, you released too late.
Okay, we already are mortally embarrassed.

conversations.title: Go the Hooli news website
conversations.body: Obviously, you don't have your Hooli news alerts up to date. Go to the site. I'll wait.
Go to the Hooli news website.
Okay. It's an ad.
Um, it's an ad. Hold on.
Just wait four seconds, and you can click to skip it.
Just wait four seconds and then you can click it.
No, it's the kind where you have to watch the whole thing.
It's the whole ad kind.
I thought we stopped doing those. Goddamn it.

conversations.title: Meinertzhagen's haversack
conversations.body: No one's heard of Meinertzhagen's haversack?
Of course I have, Jared. Just explain it to them.
Well, it's a principle of military deception. Essentially, it means you have to continue to act the part. So, as far as anyone knows, we're still building a box that we hate. We need to act like it.
That's exactly right. If we do anything differently, Barker's going to be onto us. We have to keep complaining about Barker. We have to keep bitching about the box.
We have to keep making fun of your gold chain. We have to. We don't have any other choice, Dinesh.

conversations.title: Buy Pied Piper?
conversations.body: If you hadn't blackmailed me into this arbitration, I was gonna have to go in front of the Hooli Board of Directors and ask for $250 million to buy you out.
Wow. $250 million?

Believe it or not, your algorithm is the only way to make Nucleus work. I was ready to pay whatever it took. Let me ask you this. If I offered you 10 million for Pied Piper right now, before we even go in there, would you take it?
Really? You'd do that?
No, of course not. I'm about to get it for free. I'm just f**king with you. I'm sure you'll come up with plenty more once-in-a-lifetime ideas, Richard. Or not.

conversations.title: On fire
conversations.body: It says, "Aim at the base of the fire." That's the servers.
If you hit those servers, you kill our livestream, Jared.
I don't know what to do. Should we do verbal SWOT analysis?

conversations.title: Car problems
conversations.body: I had to sell my McLaren.
Yeah, but there's a Maserati in the driveway.
Who gives a f**k? That has doors that open like this. Not like this. Or like this. So it's all f**ked.

conversations.title: How do we get a client?
conversations.body: What if we didn't do that? What if, instead, we got our own client like EndFrame has?
That's not really how it works, Gilfoyle. You can't just go get a client.
Why not?
'Cause it's not that easy.
Why not?
'Cause EndFrame worked that Intersite deal for months, kicking every detail of the contract and SLA back and forth, promising tons of custom features. And you can't just make that stuff up.
What if I didn't have to make it up? What if I had every detail of their deal on my computer right in front of me?
I'm sorry, um Are you just asking what if or do you actually have this information?
Gilfoyle, please don't tell me that you hacked into EndFrame's system.
Okay. I won't tell you that.
W-Well, did you hack into it or not?

My feeling is if you're the CEO of a company and you're dumb enough to leave your login info on a Post-it note on your desk, while the people that you f**king ripped off are physically in your office, it's not a hack. It's barely social engineering. It's more like natural selection.
f**king ninja.

conversations.title: New products by Hooli
conversations.body: Truth be told, we kind of put all our eggs into this basket, but we do have the kick-ass potato cannon, though. Although, actually, this one is broken. We tried to put a Mr. Potato Head in it, and it did not like that.

conversations.title: Welcome home
conversations.body: What about all your other "incubees"?

I've heard quite a few exciting pitches over the last week, but I'll be forced to forgo those opportunities because of your mediocrity. You see, Richard, when I invited you into my incubator, I promised to get you ready for the outside world. But I failed to do that. I wouldn't trust you out there in the real world as far as I could throw you. And to be honest, I could probably throw you all the way across the front yard.
Okay, but I don't want to stay here.
I don't want you to either, Richard. So it's agreed. Welcome home, fellas. Should we smoke some pot to celebrate?

conversations.title: Hooli XYZ announcement
conversations.body: I give you Dr. Bannerchek, the one and only man fit to be the first head dreamer of Hooli XYZ. Also I give you the one and only man fit to be his co-head dreamer, our very own Nelson Bighetti, otherwise known around here as "Baghead". Come on up here, Baghead.

conversations.title: A wide spoon
conversations.body: You see this, Richard? What is this?
A spoon?

It's a wide spoon. In fact, the only spoon type that is left in this drawer. I specifically posted a note on the refrigerator saying that the more narrow spoons be reserved for the eating for Fage yogurt by me.

conversations.title: Rename Jared
conversations.body: My only concern here, and it's a small one, um, he's also named Jared. Will it be confusing with two Jareds? If we hire him, I can always go back to my real name Donald.
No, that's too big a hassle. We'll just go with "other Jared." OJ, for short.
I know a name is just a sound somebody makes when they need you, but shouldn't this much-newer Jared be "other Jared"?
You should be flattered. OJ Simpson is one of the most recognizable people on the face of the planet.

conversations.title: Hooli was like an abusive spouse to me...
conversations.body: But Hooli was like an abusive spouse to me. You know, like that guy who married Julia Roberts in "Sleeping With The Enemy"? It was dehumanizing. But then, you, Richard, you pulled me out of the life and you gave me hope and you gave me a sense of self-worth. Like Richard Gere did to Julia Roberts in "Pretty Woman.
This is weird.
Every day here has been like that shopping-spree scene. I'm putting on hats.
Richard, I'd understand if you took it, but watching you end up over there would break my heart.
What, like Julia Roberts from "My Best Friend's Wedding"?
I never saw it.

Anyway, next thing you know, we IPO, stock triples in a day and AOL gobbles us up. All of a sudden, I'm 22 years young and I'm worth 1.2 billion. Now a couple decades later, I'm worth 1.4. You do the math.
Okay. Well, that's a gain of $200 million over 20 years. Um, 16.66 repeating. Uh, that's less than 1% return. Inflation is, like, 1.7. I think CDs are 2%. So that's less than a CD.
You're not worried about the lawsuit?
Sh*t, no. I got three nannies suing me right now, one of them for no reason.
The guy has calf implants, Richard.
How do they look?

conversations.title: Add ROI
conversations.body: ROI. ROI. You know what that stands for?
Uh, return on inv...
No. Radio on Internet.
(points at Jared) This guy f**ks
You know, Russ, I've been known to f**k myself.
Synergy, bitches. Know what that means?
Does it mean taking a stack of cash and lighting it on fire?

Dress unattractively when you tell them. I read a study. The less sexual interest they feel for you, the less perturbing it will be. It sounds strange, but it's credible. May I suggest the beige ensemble in which you came to work Tuesday?

conversations.title: dress-sh*tty-to-ease-the-pain routine
conversations.body: Can I say something here? First off, Monica, you're not fooling any of us for even a second with your dress-sh*tty-to-ease-the-pain routine. It's a classic chick break-up move, and you're not very good at it either. You look great.
Yeah, beige is a good color for you. You're a true autumn.

conversations.title: Unexpected death of Peter Gregory
conversations.body: He was in the Serengeti on safari and he had just gone into his tent when a hippo wandered into the camp.
Oh, wow.
He was attacked by a hippo?
No, I guess the hippo started to charge when the guide grabbed his rifle and shot at it, but his aim was off, and...
And he shot Peter Gregory by accident?
No, he he missed, but I guess the sound of the gun startled Peter, who ran out of his tent and...
Ran right into the hippo?
No, the hippo was also startled by the noise and had run off prior to Peter exiting his tent.
So, what happened to Peter?
He hadn't run in a long time, maybe ever, and you know, he just... that was it.

conversations.title: Data Manipulation RFC
conversations.body: Last night I was watching my friends here have this argument. About, you know, manipulating data And, you know, how many datas could one guy manipulate at once and, uh And I was just I was thinking. Maybe it could be another way, you know? Something that I would call, "middle out".

conversations.title: Nucleus is the fastest platform ever
conversations.body: Anyone who tells you their platform is faster than ours better have good lawyers.

I'll admit I'm sleep challenged. I just spent 4 days trapped in a steel box out in an oil rig full of robot forklifts. But now I'm back, and I am recovering, and I am focused, and we're going to pivot. Don't lose faith guys. Look at me, look at me. We've got a great name, we've got a great team, we've got a great logo, and we've got a great name. And now we just need an idea. Let's pivot. Let's pivot.
That might be the last time we see him alive.

How much would it be worth to you if I told you I had a GPS app called @piedpiper, tracking the location of your child? I can follow your child anywhere and there is nothing you can do to stop me. Most missing children are never found. Interested, very interested, or very interested?
People may take credit for your idea and try and sue you. How awesome is that?
Uh... yeah, that's awesome.

conversations.title: My sweet subroutine
conversations.body: It's not her you're sexually attracted to, it's my code.
Shut the... That is the most disgusting f**king thing I've ever h...
Just face it, Dinesh, you're gay for my code, you're code gay.
No! No, I'm into her. Her, OK? f**k your code!
You'd like to f**k my code, wouldn't you? Hey, would you like to masturbate to the subroutine I just wrote?

conversations.title: Jian-Yang housekeeping
conversations.body: Friday, the pool cleaner comes. Do you understand?
Yes.
And tomorrow is trash day so make sure all the cans are out front.
Yes.
Now, you are under no circumstances to order any movie on demand, adult or otherwise.
Yes.
OK, has anything that I've just said confused you?
Yes.
Goddamn it!
We may be fine. We may be totally fine. We also may be totally f**ked. I'll let you know either way.
There's been some developments. You know how I f**ked Melcher's old wife? I f**ked his new wife too.
What?
Don't worry, he's not gonna find out. I left way before he got back last night, and I didn't go back this morning until twenty minutes after he'd left.
You went back?

conversations.title: The boat guy
conversations.body: Oh, hey, did I tell you? I'm getting a boat.
Wow.
And a boat guy to take care of it. You have to have a boat guy.
Oh yeah, you've gotta have a boat guy.
Are the judges allowed to send us through to the finals immediately after we present or they have to wait until everybody has gone?
What? I was just asking what everybody was thinking.
She invited me to her room to watch Cloud Atlas later tonight.
Oh yeah, that means she wants you to lay her.
Is that definitive?
I mean, nobody can watch more than like a minute of that film.

conversations.title: Failure is contagious
conversations.body: Six months ago, these guys had 35 million and Series B Financing. Now The Carver's here doing teardown.
He's basically moving their carcass to the cloud.
Don't touch anything. Failure is contagious.
Are you sure that she didn't ask Gilfoyle for a danish and maybe you misheard her?
You're probably right, she just wanted to f**k a Danish.
Looks like Gilfoyle and his lady Satanist are back from the airport.
Can you imagine what kind of sh*t-show this one's gonna be? He says that she has an Amy Winehouse vibe. What does that mean? All tatted-up and nowhere to go.
Hooked on OxyContin?
Decomposing?
I'd have sex with that if you hose the Gilfoyle off of her.
It's weird having a girl in the house. There's a very strange energy.

conversations.title: Pakistani Denzel
conversations.body: I'm much more handsome than you are. No, my face is completely symmetrical. You know what my nickname was when I was a kid?
What?
Pakistani Denzel.

To be honest, elements of this arrangement still trouble me. However, I have not had a lot of sexual experiences. So I feel it may be foolish to turn this down. So as long as Gilfoyle is not in the room and I can verify that the door is locked then I have concluded that yes I would love to have sexual relations with you Tara. Yeah.
He's trying to turn us into corporate rock, Richard. We are punk rock.
Actually, you know, I think a better analogy would be jazz. Like we riff and improvise around a central theme to create one cohesive piece of music.

conversations.title: Naming for the company
conversations.body: Are you f**king serious? Lowercase letters? Twitter, lowercase "t". Google, lowercase "g". Facebook, lowercase "f". Every f**king company in the Valley has lowercase letters. Why? Because it's safe.
I didn't turn down ten million dollars because of Peter Gregory, Monica! I turned it down because of you!
However angry he is, I am one-tenth as angry. Because one of the ten million would've been mine... because I own ten percent...
I know.

conversations.title: Introducing Scrum
conversations.body: And that, gentlemen, is scrum. Welcome to the next eight weeks of our lives.
This just became a job.
No, no, no! Close it! Look at this left from the previous tenant. Unbelievable. I can't believe I didn't enter the garage until this point. I mean, is that marijuanas?

conversations.title: Hooli Chat is awesome
conversations.body: f**k you, the audio's still working! Audio worked a hundred f**king years ago, you f**king piece of sh*t!
It's Chuy Ramirez? I'm impressed. He sold a mural today for a half-million bucks.
It wasn't on a garage door, was it?

conversations.title: Peter Gregory doesn't care?
conversations.body: Doesn't Peter Gregory want what's best for the company?
Look, I'm going to be straight with you. Peter Gregory doesn't care.
About?
You.
Wait. Just him, or both of us?
Any of you; Pied Piper.
Okay, uhh, then why did he back us? Just to piss off Gavin Belson? He spent $200,000 to piss of Gavin Belson?
Yeah, that's nothing. Peter would spend millions just to mildly annoy Gavin. These are billionaires, Richard. Annoying each other means more to them than we'll make in a lifetime.
I see. And you conveniently forgot to mention any of this when you were convincing me to turn down 10 million dollars. And now I'm in the middle of some pissing contest between two billionaires?
In fairness, Gavin only offered the $10 million because we started pursuing you.

Yes, but he offered it to me, Monica. He offered 10 million dollars! And I didn't take it because you came to me when I was puking and freaking out and told me that Peter Gregory believed in me, when in reality, he didn't give a flying f**k!
Richard...
I didn't turn down 10 million dollars because of Peter Gregory, Monica. I turned it down because of you!
However angry he is, I am one tenth as angry. Because one of the 10 million would have been mine, because I own 10%...
I know.
...of Pied Piper.
I know!
f**k Erlich. I turned down 10 million dollars to build this thing. You want vision? I will show you f**king vision!
I like this new angry side of you. Being around angry people relaxes me because I know where I stand.

conversations.title: Remove fish
conversations.body: I eat the fish.

I understand you eat the fish. But when you clean the fish you can't leave the fish head and guts and sh*t in the sink. Because the whole house smells like a bait station. So you gotta put it in the trash and then take the trash out. Do you understand?
Yes. I eat the fish.
Motherf**k!
I always knew I was missing something, and then when someone explained the concept of "game". I remember very distinctly thinking, "That's what I don't have".
You know, I wish this was Roman times. You know? Life was simpler back then.
Simpler for you. I would have been a slave.
There's still time.
Are you dressed like Steve Jobs?
Oh, am I? Well, I suppose Steve and I always have shared a similar aesthetic.
Dinesh, leave it unbuttoned. We want you to look like sh*t. Makes for a better "before" photo.
But you're wearing a jacket.
Yeah, because I'm the genius marketer. I'm not a code freak like you guys. Besides, I'm wearing sandals so I am iconoclasting a little bit.

conversations.title: How to build a vision for your startup
conversations.body: You know, I turned down ten million dollars to build this thing. You want vision, I will show you f**king vision.
I like this new angry side to you. Being around angry people relaxes me, because I know where I stand.
Jared. I have no vision.
Yes, you do. I believe in you.
No, no, I literally have no vision. All I see is stars and swirls. I cannot see right now.

conversations.title: We have an intern program?
conversations.body: Since when do we have an intern program?
We don't. And when Keith finds that out, it's going to be a very valuable business lesson for him.
You know who else is Canadian? Justin Bieber. The Hitler of music.
Hitler actually played the bassoon. So technically Hitler was the Hitler of music.

conversations.title: The visa issue
conversations.body: Hey, Dinesh. Dinesh. I'm on the phone with the bank and they say they need an extra form for your payroll, because of your visa?
Visa? What visa? I'm a f**king US citizen.
(on phone) I have Dinesh Chugtai here, and he's pretty irate because... Oh, I see. Bertram Gilfoyle is the foreign national. Citizen of Canada. Okay, thank you.
You're Canadian?
Your "borders" are merely a construct. I prefer to think of myself as a citizen of the world.
Do you mind just sending them the form so they know you're here legally?
Yes, I mind. And also I may not be. To wit, maybe you could make out my checks to cash? Or bitcoin.
I didn't know I was working with an illegal.
The irony.
Inferior products win out all the time.
Like Jesus over Satan.
I was going to say VHS over Beta.
My name's only Jared because Gavin called me that on my first day. My real name is Donald.

conversations.title: Revolutionary ideas at Hooli
conversations.body: If we can make your audio and video files smaller, we can make cancer smaller. And hunger. And... AIDS.

conversations.title: Picking the name
conversations.body: Richard, a name defines a company. It has to be something primal, something that you can scream out during intercourse. Like Aviato.
Uuuuber!
Gooooogle!
Huuuuuulu!
Exactly, right. Pied Piper!
I'm so sorry. Your voice doesn't really reach that register when you ejaculate, does it?
No, it's just, everyone was doing it, I was just chiming in.

conversations.title: Where is Richard?
conversations.body: Where's Richard? Why isn't he in here for this?
I think he was out back, wishing he'd taken the ten million dollars.
No, I just saw him in his room, wishing he had taken the ten million dollars.
What about, "Dwarfism 2.0"?
Where's "Dwarfism 1.0"?
Just in the world.
Oh.

conversations.title: We had a handshake
conversations.body: (talking to Arnold on the phone) We had a handshake deal. And that may not mean a lot to you, but where I come from, that means a whole lot. Ok, you agreed to sell me that name for a thousand dollars. So let me ask you this? Are you an honest man or are you a goddamn liar? Ok. Yes, same address? Good, yeah, great. See you then.
Dude, that was f**king badass. What did he say?
He said he was gonna get in his truck, drive down here and beat the living sh*t out of me.
Why did you say that was your address? - Say any other address.
If you keep screaming your name, it forces the assailant to acknowledge you as a human.
